# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: diode-bridge
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:diode-bridge/1n400x-rectifier-diodes] The **1N400x** (or 1N4001 or 1N4000) series is a family of popular one-ampere general-purpose silicon rectifier diodes commonly used in AC adapters for common household appliances.
[src:diode-bridge/1n400x-rectifier-diodes] This JEDEC device number series is available in the DO-41 axial package.
[src:diode-bridge/1n400x-rectifier-diodes] Diodes with similar ratings are available in SMA and MELF surface mount packages (in other part number series).
[src:diode-bridge/1n400x-rectifier-diodes] The **1N540x** (or 1N5400) series is a similarly popular family of diodes rated 3 Amperes, which has a larger DO-201AD axial package to dissipate heat better.
[src:diode-bridge/1n400x-rectifier-diodes] The 1N400x series was originally introduced by Motorola's Semiconductor Products Division and registered at JEDEC in 1963 as silicon power rectifiers used primarily for military and industrial applications.
[src:diode-bridge/1n400x-rectifier-diodes] It appeared in the Motorola *Semiconductor Data Manual* in 1965, as replacements for 1N2609 through 1N2617.
[src:diode-bridge/1n400x-rectifier-diodes] The 1N540x series were announced in *Electrical Design News* in 1968, along with the now lesser-known 1.5 A 1N5391 series.
[src:diode-bridge/1n400x-rectifier-diodes] These devices are widely used and recommended for general-purpose power-frequency rectifier use.
[src:diode-bridge/1n400x-rectifier-diodes] They are commonly used as rectifiers in AC adapters of electrical appliances to convert AC to DC, and are also used in other types of power converters, or as freewheeling diodes to protect circuits from inductive loads.
[src:diode-bridge/1n400x-rectifier-diodes] These are fairly low-speed rectifier diodes, being inefficient for square waves of more than 15 kHz.
[src:diode-bridge/1n400x-rectifier-diodes] They are not designed for switching applications; datasheets often do not specify any information on their turn-on and turn-off characteristics.
[src:diode-bridge/1n400x-rectifier-diodes] Compared with signal diodes, rectifier diodes generally have higher current ratings, can have much higher reverse voltage ratings, but have higher leakage current and greater junction capacitance.
[src:diode-bridge/1n400x-rectifier-diodes] The following table lists part numbers in the 1N400x, 1N540x, and other popular general-purpose silicon rectifier diode families.
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] Historically, vibrator-driven switches or motor-driven commutators have also been used for mechanical rectifiers and synchronous rectification.
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] Active rectification has many applications.
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] It is frequently used for arrays of photovoltaic panels to avoid reverse current flow that can cause overheating with partial shading while giving minimum power loss.
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] It is also used in switched-mode power supplies (SMPS).
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] The constant voltage drop of a standard p-n junction diode is typically between 0.7 V and 1.7 V, causing significant power loss in the diode.
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] Electric power depends on current and voltage: the power loss rises proportional to both current and voltage.
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] In low voltage converters (around 10 volts and less), the voltage drop of a diode (typically around 0.7 to 1 volt for a silicon diode at its rated current) has an adverse effect on efficiency.
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] One classic solution replaces standard silicon diodes with Schottky diodes, which exhibit very low voltage drops (as low as 0.3 volts).
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] However, even Schottky rectifiers can be significantly more lossy than the synchronous type, notably at high currents and low voltages.
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] When addressing very low-voltage converters, such as a buck converter power supply for a computer CPU (with a voltage output around 1 volt, and many amperes of output current), Schottky rectification does not provide adequate efficiency.
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] In such applications, active rectification becomes necessary.
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] Replacing a diode with an actively controlled switching element such as a MOSFET is the heart of active rectification.
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] MOSFETs have a constant very low resistance when conducting, known as on-resistance (RDS(on)).
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] A typical modern MOSFET has an on-resistance of less than an ohm, with many high-performance devices having specifications of on the order of 10 mΩ or less.
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] The voltage drop across the transistor is then much lower, causing a reduction in power loss and a gain in efficiency.
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] However, Ohm's law governs the voltage drop across the MOSFET, meaning that at high currents, the drop can exceed that of a diode.
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] This limitation is usually dealt with either by placing several transistors in parallel, thereby reducing the current through each individual one, or by using a device with more active area (on FETs, a device-equivalent of parallel).
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] The control circuitry for active rectification usually uses comparators to sense the voltage of the input AC and open the transistors at the correct times to allow current to flow in the correct direction.
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] The timing is very important, as a short circuit across the input power must be avoided and can easily be caused by one transistor turning on before another has turned off.
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] Active rectifiers also clearly still need the smoothing capacitors present in passive examples to provide smoother power than rectification does alone.
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] A MOSFET actively controlled to act as a rectifier—actively turned on to allow current in one direction but actively turned off to block current from flowing the other direction—is sometimes called an *ideal diode*.
[src:diode-bridge/active-rectification] Such a MOSFET-based ideal diode is not to be confused with an op-amp based super diode, often called a precision rectifier.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] The **alt attribute** is the HTML attribute used in HTML and XHTML documents to specify alternative text (**alt text**) that is to be displayed in place of an element that cannot be rendered.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] The alt attribute is used for short descriptions, with longer descriptions using the longdesc attribute.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] The standards organization for the World Wide Web, the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), recommends that every image displayed through HTML have an alt attribute, though the alt attribute does not need to contain text.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] The lack of proper alt attributes on website images has led to several accessibility-related lawsuits.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] The alt attribute is used to increase accessibility and user friendliness, including for blind internet users who rely on special software for web browsing.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] The use of the alt attribute for images displayed within HTML is part of W3C's Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG).
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] Screen readers and text-based web browsers read the alt attribute in place of the image.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] The text within the alt attribute substitutes the image when copy-pasted as text and makes images more machine-readable, which improves search engine optimization (SEO).
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] The attribute was first introduced in the HTML 1.2 draft in 1993 to provide support for text-based browsers.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] In HTML 4.01, which was released in 1999, the attribute was made to be a requirement for the img and area tags.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] It is optional for the input tag and the deprecated applet tag.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] Internet Explorer 7 and earlier render text in alt attributes as tooltip text, which is not compliant with the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C)'s HTML standards.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] This behavior led many web developers to misuse the alt attribute when they wished to display tooltips containing additional information about images, instead of using the title attribute that was intended for that use.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] As of Internet Explorer 8, released in 2009, alt attributes no longer render as tooltips on Internet Explorer.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] The text in the alt attribute is used to replace the image when the image cannot be loaded, without changing the intended meaning of the page's contents.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] The W3C's web content accessibility guidelines state that the alt attribute is used to convey the meaning and intent of the image, rather than being a literal description of the image itself.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] For example, an alt attribute for an image of an institution's logo should convey that it is the institution's logo rather than describing details of what the logo looks like.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] The alt attribute is intended to be used for short and concise descriptions of the image.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] Longer descriptions can be given using the longdesc attribute, which provides more detailed information and complements but does not replace the alt attribute.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] A screen reader such as Orca will read out the alt text in place of the image.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] A text-based web browser such as Lynx will display the alt text instead of the image (or will display the value attribute if the image is a clickable button).
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] A graphical browser typically will display only the image, and will display the alt text only if the user views the image's properties, or has configured the browser not to display images, or if the browser was unable to retrieve or to decode the image.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] The use of descriptions in the alt attribute improves search engine optimization and allows image-specific search engines, such as Google Images, to search for and display relevant images that are used on websites in search results.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] For non-image search results, the text within the alt attribute is read by search engines the same way that regular text on the page is read.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] The W3C recommends that images that convey no information, but are purely decorative, be specified in CSS rather than in the HTML markup.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] If decorative images are rendered using HTML that do not add to the content and provide no additional information, then the W3C recommends that a blank alt attribute be included in the form of `alt=""`.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] This makes the page more navigable for users of screen readers or non-graphical browsers by skipping over images that do not convey any meaning.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] If no alt attribute has been supplied, then browsers that cannot display the image will not overlook the image but instead will read or display the URL or another identifying marker.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] This creates ambiguity since the user is generally unable to determine from a bare reading of a URL if the image is relevant to the text or if it is a purely decorative element of the webpage.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] A 2021 Google Lighthouse audit showed that 27% of alt text attributes audited were empty, despite the fact that the majority of those images were non-decorative informational images.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] There have been many lawsuits over website accessibility and the lack of proper alt attributes on websites.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] *Maguire v Sydney Organising Committee for the Olympic Games* was a 2000 lawsuit in which a blind man in Australia sued the Sydney Organising Committee for the Olympic Games because their website www.olympics.com was not accessible to him because of the lack of alt attributes on images.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] The Australian Human Rights Commission ruled that the website had discriminated against him for failing to conform to accessibility standards that enable blind individuals to navigate websites.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] During the lawsuit, the Australian commonwealth, state and territory governments issued a joint statement through the Department of Broadband, Communications and the Digital Economy that they were adopting the W3C's accessibility guidelines for all .gov.au websites.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] In the United States, there have been several high-profile lawsuits involving the lack of alt attributes on images that cite a violation of the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA).
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] The United States Department of Justice gives the lack of alt attributes as an example of a barrier to website accessibility.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] Target Corp.* was a 2006 class-action lawsuit that alleged that Target.com violated the ADA because the images did not use alt attributes.
[src:diode-bridge/alt-attribute] This lawsuit set a legal precedent in the United States for website accessibility and compliance with the ADA.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:diode-bridge/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:diode-bridge/anderson-s-bridge] In electronics, **Anderson's bridge** is a bridge circuit used to measure the self-inductance of the coil.
[src:diode-bridge/anderson-s-bridge] It enables measurement of inductance by utilizing other circuit components like resistors and capacitors.
[src:diode-bridge/anderson-s-bridge] Anderson's bridge was invented by Alexander Anderson in 1891.
[src:diode-bridge/anderson-s-bridge] He modified Maxwell's inductance capacitance bridge so that it gives very accurate measurement of self-inductance.
[src:diode-bridge/anderson-s-bridge] The balance conditions for Anderson's bridge or, equivalently the values of the self-inductance and resistance of the given coil can be found using basic circuit analysis techniques such as KCL, KVL and using phasors.
[src:diode-bridge/anderson-s-bridge] Consider the circuit diagram of Anderson's bridge in the given figure.
[src:diode-bridge/anderson-s-bridge] Let **L1** be the self-inductance and **R1** be the electrical resistance of the coil under consideration.
[src:diode-bridge/anderson-s-bridge] Since the voltmeter is ideally assumed to have nearly infinite impedance, the currents in branches **ab** and **bc** and those in the branches **de** and **ec** are taken to be equal.
[src:diode-bridge/anderson-s-bridge] Since the analysis is being made under the balanced condition of the bridge, it can be said that the voltage drop across the voltmeter is essentially zero.
[src:diode-bridge/anderson-s-bridge] The Anderson's bridge can also be used the other way round- that is, it can be used to measure the capacitance of an unknown capacitor using an inductor coil whose self-inductance and electrical resistance have been pre-determined to a high degree of precision.
[src:diode-bridge/anderson-s-bridge] An interesting point to note is the fact that the measured self-inductance of the coil does not change even on taking dielectric loss within the capacitor into account.
[src:diode-bridge/anderson-s-bridge] Another advantage of using this modified bridge is that unlike the variable capacitor used in Maxwell bridge, it makes use of a fixed capacitor which is relatively quite cheaper.
[src:diode-bridge/anderson-s-bridge] One of the obvious difficulties associated with Anderson's bridge are the relatively complex balance equation calculations compared to the Maxwell bridge.
[src:diode-bridge/anderson-s-bridge] The circuit connections and computations are similarly more cumbersome in comparison to the Maxwell bridge.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] A **band-pass filter** or **bandpass filter** (**BPF**) is a device that passes frequencies within a certain range and rejects (attenuates) frequencies outside that range.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] It is the inverse of a *band-stop filter*.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] In electronics and signal processing, a filter is usually a two-port circuit or device which removes frequency components of a signal (an alternating voltage or current).
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] A band-pass filter allows through components in a specified band of frequencies, called its *passband* but blocks components with frequencies above or below this band.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] This contrasts with a high-pass filter, which allows through components with frequencies above a specific frequency, and a low-pass filter, which allows through components with frequencies below a specific frequency.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] In digital signal processing, in which signals represented by digital numbers are processed by computer programs, a band-pass filter is a computer algorithm that performs the same function.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] The term band-pass filter is also used for optical filters, sheets of colored material which allow through a specific band of light frequencies, commonly used in photography and theatre lighting, and acoustic filters which allow through sound waves of a specific band of frequencies.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] An example of an analogue electronic band-pass filter is an RLC circuit (a resistor–inductor–capacitor circuit).
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] These filters can also be created by combining a low-pass filter with a high-pass filter.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] A *bandpass signal* is a signal containing a band of frequencies not adjacent to zero frequency, such as a signal that comes out of a bandpass filter.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] An ideal bandpass filter would have a completely flat passband: all frequencies within the passband would be passed to the output without amplification or attenuation, and would completely attenuate all frequencies outside the passband.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] In practice, no bandpass filter is ideal.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] The filter does not attenuate all frequencies outside the desired frequency range completely; in particular, there is a region just outside the intended passband where frequencies are attenuated, but not rejected.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] This is known as the filter roll-off, and it is usually expressed in dB of attenuation per octave or decade of frequency.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Generally, the design of a filter seeks to make the roll-off as narrow as possible, thus allowing the filter to perform as close as possible to its intended design.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Often, this is achieved at the expense of pass-band or stop-band *ripple*.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] The bandwidth of the filter is simply the difference between the upper and lower cutoff frequencies.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] The shape factor is the ratio of bandwidths measured using two different attenuation values to determine the cutoff frequency, e.g., a shape factor of 2:1 at 30/3 dB means the bandwidth measured between frequencies at 30 dB attenuation is twice that measured between frequencies at 3 dB attenuation.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] A band-pass filter can be characterized by its Q factor.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] The Q-factor is the reciprocal of the fractional bandwidth.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] A high-Q filter will have a narrow passband and a low-Q filter will have a wide passband.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] These are respectively referred to as *narrow-band* and *wide-band* filters.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Bandpass filters are widely used in wireless transmitters and receivers.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] The main function of such a filter in a transmitter is to limit the bandwidth of the output signal to the band allocated for the transmission.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] This prevents the transmitter from interfering with other stations.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] In a receiver, a bandpass filter allows signals within a selected range of frequencies to be heard or decoded, while preventing signals at unwanted frequencies from getting through.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Signals at frequencies outside the band which the receiver is tuned at, can either saturate or damage the receiver.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Additionally they can create unwanted mixing products that fall in band and interfere with the signal of interest.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Wideband receivers are particularly susceptible to such interference.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] A bandpass filter also optimizes the signal-to-noise ratio and sensitivity of a receiver.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] In both transmitting and receiving applications, well-designed bandpass filters, having the optimum bandwidth for the mode and speed of communication being used, maximize the number of signal transmitters that can exist in a system, while minimizing the interference or competition among signals.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Outside of electronics and signal processing, one example of the use of band-pass filters is in the atmospheric sciences.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] It is common to band-pass filter recent meteorological data with a period range of, for example, 3 to 10 days, so that only cyclones remain as fluctuations in the data fields.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] A 4th order electrical bandpass filter can be simulated by a vented box in which the contribution from the rear face of the driver cone is trapped in a sealed box, and the radiation from the front surface of the cone is into a ported chamber.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] This modifies the resonance of the driver.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] In its simplest form a compound enclosure has two chambers.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] The dividing wall between the chambers holds the driver; typically only one chamber is ported.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] If the enclosure on each side of the woofer has a port in it then the enclosure yields a 6th order band-pass response.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] These are considerably harder to design and tend to be very sensitive to driver characteristics.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] As in other reflex enclosures, the ports may generally be replaced by passive radiators if desired.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] An eighth order bandpass box is another variation which also has a narrow frequency range.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] They are often used in sound pressure level competitions, in which case a bass tone of a specific frequency would be used versus anything musical.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] They are complicated to build and must be done quite precisely in order to perform nearly as intended.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Bandpass filters can also be used outside of engineering-related disciplines.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] A leading example is the use of bandpass filters to extract the business cycle component in economic time series.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] This reveals more clearly the expansions and contractions in economic activity that dominate the lives of the public and the performance of diverse firms, and therefore is of interest to a wide audience of economists and policy-makers, among others.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Economic data usually has quite different statistical properties than data in say, electrical engineering.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] It is very common for a researcher to directly carry over traditional methods such as the "ideal" filter, which has a perfectly sharp gain function in the frequency domain.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] However, in doing so, substantial problems can arise that can cause distortions and make the filter output extremely misleading.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] As a poignant and simple case, the use of an "ideal" filter on white noise (which could represent for example stock price changes) creates a false cycle.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] The use of the nomenclature "ideal" implicitly involves a greatly fallacious assumption except on scarce occasions.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Nevertheless, the use of the "ideal" filter remains common despite its limitations.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Fortunately, band-pass filters are available that steer clear of such errors, adapt to the data series at hand, and yield more accurate assessments of the business cycle fluctuations in major economic series like Real GDP, Investment, and Consumption - as well as their sub-components.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] An early work, published in the Review of Economics and Statistics in 2003, more effectively handles the kind of data (stochastic rather than deterministic) arising in macroeconomics.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] In this paper entitled "General Model-Based Filters for Extracting Trends and Cycles in Economic Time Series", Andrew Harvey and Thomas Trimbur develop a class of adaptive band pass filters.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] These have been successfully applied in various situations involving business cycle movements in myriad nations in the international economy.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Band pass filters can be implemented in 4G and 5G wireless communication systems.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Hussaini et al.(2015) stated that, in the application of wireless communication, radio frequency noise is a major concern.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] In the current development of 5G technology, planer band pass filters are used to suppress RF noises and removing unwanted signals.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Combine, hairpin, parallel-coupled line, step impedance and stub impedance are the designs of experimenting the band pass filter to achieve low insertion loss with a compact size.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] The necessity of adopting asymmetric frequency response is in behalf of reducing the number of resonators, insertion loss, size and cost of circuit production.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] 4-pole cross-coupled band pass filter is designed by Hussaini et al.(2015).
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] This band pass filter is designed to cover the 2.5-2.6 GHz and 3.4-3.7 GHz spectrum for the 4G and 5G wireless communication applications respectively.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] It is developed and extended from 3-pole single-band band pass filter, where an additional resonator is applied to a 3-pole single-band band pass filter.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] The advanced band pass filter has a compact size with a simple structure, which is convenient for implementation.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Moreover, the stop band rejection and selectivity present a good performance in RF noise suppression.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Insertion loss is very low when covering the 4G and 5G spectrum, while providing good return loss and group delay.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Energy scavengers are devices that search for energy from the environment efficiently.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Band pass filters can be implemented to energy scavengers by converting energy generated from vibration into electric energy.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] The band pass filter designed by Shahruz (2005), is an ensemble of cantilever beams, which is called the beam-mass system.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Ensemble of beam-mass systems can be transformed into a band pass filter when appropriate dimensions of beams and masses are chosen.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Although the process of designing a mechanical band pass filter is advanced, further study and work are still required to design more flexible band pass filters to suit large frequency intervals.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] This mechanical band pass filter could be used on vibration sources with distinct peak-power frequencies.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] In neuroscience, visual cortical simple cells were first shown by David Hubel and Torsten Wiesel to have response properties that resemble Gabor filters, which are band-pass.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] In astronomy, band-pass filters are used to allow only a single portion of the light spectrum into an instrument.
[src:diode-bridge/bandpass] Band-pass filters can help with finding where stars lie on the main sequence, identifying redshifts, and many other applications.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] In signal processing, a **band-stop filter** or **band-rejection filter** is a filter that passes most frequencies unaltered, but attenuates those in a specific range to very low levels.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] It is the inverse of a *band-pass filter*.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] A **notch filter** is a band-stop filter with a narrow stopband (high Q factor).
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] Other names include "band limit filter", "T-notch filter", "band-elimination filter", and "band-reject filter".
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] Typically, the width of the stopband is 1 to 2 decades (that is, the highest frequency attenuated is 10 to 100 times the lowest frequency attenuated).
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] However, in the audio band, a notch filter has high and low frequencies that may be only semitones apart.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] From the figure of the frequency response of an ideal band-stop filter, it's obvious that the band-stop filter is simply an inverted band-pass filter where they share same definition of bandwidth, pass band, stop band and center frequency.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] The attenuation should be infinite in the stop band and be zero in the two pass bands for an ideal band-stop filter.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] Band-stop filters are designed by the combination of a low-pass filter and a high-pass filter in a parallel configuration.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] Overlapping does not occur in the summation of high-pass filter and low-pass filter during the design of band-stop filter.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] The difference in the starting and ending frequency points causes the two filters to connect effectively without any overlapping.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] Band-stop filter can be represented as a combination of low-pass and high-pass filters if the bandwidth is wide enough that the two filters do not interact too much.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] A more general approach is to design as a low-pass prototype filter which can then be transformed into a bandstop.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] The simple notch filter shown can be directly analysed.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] Here $\omega _{z}$ is zero circular frequency and $\omega _{p}$ is the pole circular frequency.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] Zero frequency is the cutoff frequency and $\omega _{p}$ sets the type of the notch filter: standard notch when $\omega _{z}=\omega _{p}$ , low-pass notch ( $\omega _{z}>\omega _{p}$ ) and high-pass notch ( $\omega _{z}<\omega _{p}$ ) filters.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] where $\omega _{0}$ is the central rejected frequency and $\omega _{c}>0$ is the width of the rejected band.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] This means that the filter passes all frequencies, except for the range of 59–61 Hz.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] This would be used to filter out the mains hum from the 60 Hz power line, though its higher harmonics could still be present.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] For countries where power transmission is at 50 Hz, the filter would have a 49–51 Hz range.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] When measuring the non-linearities of power amplifiers, a very narrow notch filter can be very useful to avoid the carrier frequency.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] Use of the filter may ensure that the maximum input power of a spectrum analyser used to detect spurious content will not be exceeded.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] A notch filter, usually a simple LC circuit, is used to remove a specific interfering frequency.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] This is a technique used with radio receivers that are so close to a transmitter that it swamps all other signals.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] The wave trap is used to remove or greatly reduce the signal from the nearby transmitter.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] Most affordable software-defined radios (SDR) on the market today suffer from limited dynamic and operating ranges.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] In other words, in real-world operating environments, a SDR can easily be saturated by a strong signal.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] In particular FM broadcast signals are very strong and nearly everywhere.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] These signals can prevent a SDR from processing other weak signals.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] FM notch filters are very useful for SDR applications and have increased in their popularity.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] In optics, there are several methods of filtering selected wavelengths from a source or to a detector.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] They rely on scattering or destructive interference.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] A diffraction grating or a dispersive prism may be used to selectively redirect selected wavelengths of light within an optical system.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] In the case of transmission gratings and prisms, polychromatic light that passes through the object will be redirected according to wavelength.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] A slit may then be used to select wavelengths that are desired.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] A reflective grating may also be utilized for the same purpose, though in this case light is reflected rather than transmitted.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] Filters of this design may be high-pass, band-pass, or low-pass, depending on system configuration.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] When using optics with real materials, light will be attenuated at various wavelengths through interference with the medium through which the light traversed.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] In this sense, material selection may be utilized to selectively filter light according to the wavelengths that are minimally attenuated.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] To some extent, all real optical systems will suffer from this phenomenon.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] Alternatively, it is also possible to use an oscillating reflecting surface to cause destructive interference with reflected light along a single optical path.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] This principle is the basis for a Michelson interferometer.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] Smoothing filter is essential in many fields, such as signal and image processing, computer vision, statistics, stated by Roonizi (2021).
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] Algorithms such as quadratic variation regularization and smoothness priors are the most common way to perform signal denoising.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] These algorithms are implemented to band-stop smoothing filters and being investigated by Roonizi (2021).
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] A naive band-stop smoothing filter is raised, which is constructed by connecting a high-pass smoothing filter and a low-pass smoothing filter.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] These two smoothing filter sections are configured in parallel way.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] Moreover, it was suggested that positive noise correlation promises to obtain the best band-stop smoothing filter.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] The development of telecommunications applications raises the demand of radio frequency and microwave filters, stated by Haddi (2019).
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] Those filters are commonly used in PA systems (Public Address Systems) and speaker systems to produce audio with great quality.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] Microwave filters have high flexibility of actualization and low cost.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] The band-stop filter in the telecommunications field, has a respectable place which it is essential for microwave transceivers.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] For example, wireless communication systems make use of band-stop filters to achieve the requirement of miniaturization.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] Microstrip-line band-stop filter is convenient to implement with low cost and light weight.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] Hsieh & Wang (2005) stated that, conventional microstrip band-stop filters are made of shunt open-circuited resonators.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] They usually has the characteristic of having narrow stopband.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] However, alternating the band-stop filter to have a wide stop band response with specific design can bring huge advantage over the conventional band-stop filters.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] The advantages of the microstrip band-stop filter designed by Hsieh & Wang (2005) is its compact size and easy implementation.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] This improved band-stop filter with wide stop-band has additional amount of transmission zeros.
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] The purpose of this design is to combine a shunt open-circuited quarter-wavelength resonator with one section of quarter-wavelength frequency-selecting coupling structure, stated by Hsieh & Wang (2005).
[src:diode-bridge/bandstop-filter] As a result, a simple structured band-stop filter with easy implementation can bring advantages of lower-order resonators, great stop band performance when compared to conventional microstrip band-stop filters.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] A **diode bridge** is a bridge rectifier circuit of four diodes that is used in the process of converting alternating current (AC) from the input terminals to direct current (DC, i.e. fixed polarity) on the output terminals.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] Its function is to convert the negative voltage portions of the AC waveform to positive voltage, after which a low-pass filter can be used to smooth the result into DC.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] When used in its most common application, for conversion of an alternating-current (AC) input into a direct-current (DC) output, it is known as a **bridge rectifier**.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] A bridge rectifier provides full-wave rectification from a two-wire AC input, resulting in lower cost and weight as compared to a rectifier with a three-wire input from a transformer with a center-tapped secondary winding.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] Prior to the availability of integrated circuits, a bridge rectifier was constructed from separate diodes.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] Since about 1950, a single four-terminal component containing the four diodes connected in a bridge configuration has been available and is now available with various voltage and current ratings.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] Diodes are also used in bridge topologies along with capacitors as voltage multipliers.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] The diode bridge circuit was invented by Karol Pollak and patented in December 1895 in Great Britain and in January 1896 in Germany.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] In 1897, Leo Graetz independently invented and published a similar circuit.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] Today the circuit is sometimes referred to as a "Graetz circuit" or "Graetz bridge".
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] According to the conventional model of current flow, originally established by Benjamin Franklin and still followed by most engineers today, current flows through electrical conductors from the positive to the negative pole (defined as positive flow).
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] In actuality, free electrons in a conductor nearly always flow from the negative to the positive pole.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] In the vast majority of applications, however, the actual direction of current flow is irrelevant.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] Therefore, in the discussion below the conventional model is retained.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] The fundamental characteristic of a diode is that current can flow only one way through it, which is defined as the forward direction.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] A diode bridge uses diodes as series components to allow current to pass in the forward direction during the positive part of the AC cycle and as shunt components to redirect current flowing in the reverse direction during the negative part of the AC cycle to the opposite rails.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] When the input connected to the left corner is negative, and the input connected to the right corner is positive, current flows from the lower supply terminal to the right along the red (positive) path to the output and returns to the upper supply terminal through the blue (negative) path.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] In each case, the upper right output remains positive, and lower right output negative.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] Alternatives to the diode-bridge full-wave rectifiers are the center-tapped transformer and double-diode rectifier, and voltage doubler rectifier using two diodes and two capacitors in a bridge topology.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] With AC input, the output of a diode bridge (called a full-wave rectifier for this purpose; there is also half-wave rectification, which does not use a diode bridge) is polarized pulsating non-sinusoidal voltage of the same amplitude but twice the frequency of the input.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] It may be considered as DC voltage upon which is superimposed a very large ripple voltage.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] This kind of electric power is not very usable, because ripple is dissipated as waste heat in DC circuit components and may cause noise or distortion during circuit operation.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] So nearly all rectifiers are followed by a series of bandpass or bandstop filters and/or a voltage regulator to convert most or all of the ripple voltage into a smoother and possibly higher DC output.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] A filter may be as simple as a single sufficiently large capacitor or choke, but most power-supply filters have multiple alternating series and shunt components.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] When the ripple voltage rises, reactive power is stored in the filter components, reducing the voltage; when the ripple voltage falls, reactive power is discharged from the filter components, raising the voltage.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] The final stage of rectification may consist of a zener diode-based voltage regulator, which almost completely eliminates any residual ripple.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] The diode bridge can be generalized to rectify polyphase AC inputs.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] For example, for a three-phase AC input, a half-wave rectifier consists of three diodes, but a full-wave bridge rectifier consists of six diodes.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] A half-wave rectifier may be considered a wye connection (star connection), because it returns the current through the center (neutral) wire.
[src:diode-bridge/diode-bridge] A full-wave rectifier is more like a delta connection, although it can be connected to the three-phase source of either wye or delta and it does not use the center (neutral) wire.
